<span class="displaytext"><b>for immediate release <br/> contact:</b> kevin madden (857) 288-6390 <p align="center"> <b>(candidate last) for president to begin airing ads in south carolina</b> </p><p><b>boston, ma –</b> today, (candidate last) for president launched its newest television ad, "energy." the ad highlights governor (candidate last)'s leadership in turning around numerous companies, the 2002 salt lake city winter olympics and the commonwealth of massachusetts. the ad will begin airing as part of the campaign's rotation today in iowa and new hampshire. script and viewing links are below. </p><p>(candidate last) for president will also be expanding its television advertising to south carolina. over the next two weeks, (candidate last) for president will begin airing "energy" and "leadership" throughout south carolina. </p><p><b> <u>script for "energy" (tv:30):</u> </b> </p><p><b>ann (candidate last):</b> "every place that mitt has gone, he has solved problems that people said were nearly impossible." </p><p><b>announcer:</b> "(candidate full), the innovator who created and revolutionized american businesses, turned around major companies. </p><p>"took on the bankrupt olympics and turned them around. </p><p>"the (PARTY NAME) governor who stood up and cut spending instead of raising taxes. </p><p>"and turned around our most (PARTY NAME) state. </p><p>"leadership to turn around washington." </p><p><b>governor (candidate full):</b> "i'm (candidate full) and i approved this message." </p><p><em>to watch "energy," please see</em>: <a href="http://mitt-tv.(candidate full).com/?showid=354269">http://mitt-tv.(candidate full).com/?showid=354269</a> </p><p><b> <u>ad facts: script for "energy" (tv:30):</u> </b> </p><p><b>ann (candidate last):</b> "every place that mitt has gone, he has solved problems that people said were nearly impossible." </p><p><b>announcer:</b> "(candidate full), the innovator who created and revolutionized american businesses, turned around major companies." </p><p><b>- governor (candidate last) has "a solid reputation in the business community for turning companies around."</b> cnn's rhonda schaffler: "(candidate last) had a solid reputation in the business community for turning companies around, like staples, domino's pizza and the sports authority." (cnn's "business unusual," 1/27/02) </p><p><b>- <em>boston business journal</em>: (candidate last) "made his name as a turnaround man."</b> "bain &amp; co. was a crowning victory for (candidate last), 47, who has made his name as a turnaround man. as chief executive of bain capital inc., the venture group he was picked to launch back in 1984, he has backed and helped repair more than 50 companies. with an initial $14 million invested by the partners of bain &amp; co., bain capital has since raised $500 million in four funds, pouring dollars into companies like staples inc., brookstone and the sports authority." (beth healy, "(candidate last) puts skills in business to test," <em>boston business journal</em>, 6/10/94) </p><p><b>- <em>bloomberg</em>'s heidi pryzbyla:</b> "(candidate last)'s business record is unmatched by the current crop of leading candidates." (heidi pryzbyla, "(candidate last) finds classmate bush's management lapses unlikely hurdle," <em>bloomberg</em>, 7/1/07) </p><p><b>- <em>the boston globe</em>'s robert gavin and sacha pfeiffer:</b> "in time, (candidate last) would lead the shaky start-up from a staff of seven people managing $37 million to 115 people managing $4 billion in assets. during (candidate last)'s 15-year tenure, bain capital would post an astonishing record, on average doubling its return on realized investments every year." (robert gavin and sacha pfeiffer, "reaping profit in study, sweat," <em>the boston globe</em>, 6/26/07) </p><p><b>announcer:</b> "took on the bankrupt olympics and turned them around." </p><p><b>- <em>the associated press</em>:</b> "(candidate last) took over as head of salt lake's olympic organizing committee in february 1999 after it was revealed salt lake organizers doled out more than $1 million in cash and gifts to members of the international olympic committee to win the 2002 bid. under (candidate last)'s leadership, the games were lauded as a critical success, a model of post-sept. 11 security and turned a $100 million profit. (candidate last), a successful venture capitalist before the games, wrote a book after titled 'turnaround: crisis, leadership and the olympic games.'" (debbie hummel, "utah's 'adopted son' returns to state for presidential fundraiser," <em>the associated press</em>, 2/21/07) </p><p><b>- governor (candidate last) turned a $379 million deficit into a $100 million profit.</b> "as early as 1999, a financial crisis was looming: the games were mired in a bribery scandal and were running a $379 million deficit. (candidate last) was asked to step in, and he immediately slashed budgets and boosted sponsorships. and since the games were held just months after sept. 11, 2001, he oversaw a huge security apparatus. he now says it was one of the most difficult things he'd ever done, comparing it to 'arranging 17 super bowls a day for 17 days.' the games ended up with a $100 million profit." (marcia vickers, "the (PARTY NAME)s' mr. fix-it," <em>fortune magazine</em>, 6/27/07) </p><p><b>- <em>the boston globe</em>'s john powers: due to "(candidate last)'s energy, optimism, and executive/entrepreneurial skills, the salt lake olympics ... appear likely to be a huge success."</b> "the ioc had forced out or was about to expel 10 members who had taken nearly $1 million worth of cash and gifts from the salt lake bidders. the local organizing committee was bleeding hundreds of millions of dollars of red ink, while would-be sponsors and donors, wary of being linked to tarnished olympic rings, sat on their wallets. and utahns who had celebrated in the streets when the games were awarded were sickened and angered. now, thanks largely to (candidate last)'s energy, optimism, and executive/entrepreneurial skills, the salt lake olympics – barring an act of god or terrorism – appear likely to be a huge success." (john powers, "golden opportunity," the boston globe, 2/3/02) </p><p><b>announcer:</b> "the (PARTY NAME) governor who stood up and cut spending instead of raising taxes." </p><p><b>- governor (candidate last) closed the nearly $3 billion shortfall without tax increases.</b> "when (candidate full) became governor of massachusetts in 2003, the state had a budget gap of almost $3 billion and was losing thousands of jobs a month. in mr. (candidate last)'s four-year tenure, the deficit was eliminated without raising the sales tax or the income tax, and since the labor slump hit bottom in december 2003, the state has gained 81,000 jobs." (pam belluck, "(candidate last) candidacy puts massachusetts economy in spotlight," <em>the new york times</em>, 3/16/07) </p><p><b>- to close the budget gap, governor (candidate last) forced the legislature to pass "tremendous spending cuts."</b> "governor (candidate last) receives credit for actual spending in fy 2003, even though he entered office halfway into the fiscal year, because of the tremendous spending cuts he forced down the legislature's throat in january of 2003. facing a $650 million deficit he inherited from the previous administration, (candidate last) convinced the unfriendly state legislature to grant him unilateral power to make budget cuts and unveiled $343 million in cuts to cities, healthcare, and state agencies. this fiscal discipline continued in 2004, in which (candidate last) continued to slash 'nearly every part of state government' to close a $3 billion deficit." (the club for growth, "(candidate full)'s record on economic issues," press release, 8/21/07) </p><p><b>- in the four budgets he signed, governor (candidate last) used the line-item veto or program reduction power in an attempt to cut spending by nearly $1 billion.</b> (office of governor (candidate full), "(candidate last) signs no new tax budget in time for new fiscal year," press release, 6/30/03; office of governor (candidate full), "governor (candidate full) signs $22.402b fiscal year 2005 'no new tax' budget," press release, 6/25/04; office of governor (candidate full), "governor (candidate full) signs into law $23.8 billion budget for fiscal year '06," press release, 6/30/05; office of governor (candidate full), "governor (candidate full) signs $25.2 billion fiscal year 2007 state budget," press release, 7/8/06) </p><p><b>- the club for growth: governor (candidate last) "imposed much-needed fiscal discipline on a very liberal massachusetts legislature."</b> (the club for growth, "(candidate full)'s record on economic issues," press release, 8/21/07) </p><p><b>- massachusetts citizens for limited taxation executive director barbara anderson:</b> "there was no one else out on the horizon and with the legislature almost entirely (PARTY NAME), we felt it was necessary to have a grown-up in the corner office. ... and we were right to back him. he's been a really good friend to the taxpayers." (shawn macomber, "mighty (candidate full)," <em>the american spectator</em>, 3/06) </p><p><b>- boston's pioneer institute's steve adams:</b> "without (candidate last), we would have been slapped with a lot of new taxes." (john j. miller, "matinee mitt," <em>national review</em>, 6/20/05) </p><p><b>announcer:</b> "and turned around our most (PARTY NAME) state. leadership to turn around washington." </p><p><b>- <em>the weekly standard</em>'s terry eastland:</b> "as governor, (candidate last) has scored another turnaround, conservative in both ends and means. told during the campaign that he would inherit a deficit of between $500 million and $1.5 billion, (candidate last) discovered upon taking office a $650 million deficit in fiscal 2003 and an anticipated one of $3 billion in fiscal 2004. (candidate last) balanced the 2003 budget, and he finished 2004 with a $700 million surplus. a reviving economy helped, but (candidate last) didn't tax or borrow, and he reduced spending through government consolidation and reform." (terry eastland, "in 2008, will it be mormon in america?" <em>the weekly standard</em>, 6/6/05) </p><p><b>governor (candidate full):</b> "i'm (candidate full) and i approved this message." </p><p><em>to watch "energy," please see</em>: <a href="http://mitt-tv.(candidate full).com/?showid=354269">http://mitt-tv.(candidate full).com/?showid=354269</a></p></span>



